<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Makefile (drop-in)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words"># Spherepop Tools Makefile</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words"># Explicit, local, reversible installation</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words"># No networking, no build steps, no privilege escalation beyond install paths</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">PREFIX      ?= /usr/local
BINDIR      := $(PREFIX)/bin
MANDIR      := $(PREFIX)/share/man
MAN1DIR     := $(MANDIR)/man1</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">TOOLS := 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-lab 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-probe-goodhart 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-drift-metrics 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-check-invariants 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-sim-observer 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-audit-legibility 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-probe-refusal 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;sp-sim-apprenticeship</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">MANPAGES := $(TOOLS:%=%.1)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.PHONY: all install uninstall reinstall man install-man uninstall-man check</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">all:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Spherepop tools are scripts; nothing to build."
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Use: make install"</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">check:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Checking executability..."
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@for t in $(TOOLS); do 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;test -x usr/bin/<span class="katex-error" title="ParseError: KaTeX parse error: Expected '}', got 'EOF' at end of input: ŌĆ”RROR: usr/bin/ " style="color: rgb(204, 0, 0);"> t || { echo "ERROR: usr/bin/ </span>t not executable"; exit 1; }; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;done
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "OK"</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">install: check install-bin install-man
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Installed Spherepop tools into $(PREFIX)"</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">install-bin:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Installing tools into $(BINDIR)"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@install -d $(BINDIR)
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@for t in $(TOOLS); do 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;install -m 0755 usr/bin/<span class="katex-error" title="ParseError: KaTeX parse error: Can't use function '$' in math mode at position 4:  t $╠▓(BINDIR)/ " style="color: rgb(204, 0, 0);"> t $(BINDIR)/ </span>t; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;done</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">install-man:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Installing manpages into $(MAN1DIR)"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@install -d $(MAN1DIR)
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@for m in $(MANPAGES); do 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;install -m 0644 usr/share/man/man1/<span class="katex-error" title="ParseError: KaTeX parse error: Can't use function '$' in math mode at position 4:  m $╠▓(MAN1DIR)/ " style="color: rgb(204, 0, 0);"> m $(MAN1DIR)/ </span>m; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;done
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@command -v mandb &gt;/dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;&amp; mandb &gt;/dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1 || true</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">uninstall: uninstall-bin uninstall-man
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Uninstalled Spherepop tools from $(PREFIX)"</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">uninstall-bin:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "Removing tools from $(BINDIR)"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@for t in $(TOOLS); do 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;rm -f $(BINDIR)/$$  t; 
done</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">uninstall-man:
@echo "Removing manpages from $(MAN1DIR)"
@for m in $(MANPAGES); do 
rm -f $(MAN1DIR)/  $$m; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;done
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@command -v mandb &gt;/dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;&amp; mandb &gt;/dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1 || true</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">reinstall: uninstall install</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Why this target is epistemically safe</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This matters given your earlier concern about looking like a hacker or building ŌĆ£penetration tools.ŌĆØ</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This Makefile deliberately:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Does not compile anything</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Does not fetch dependencies</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Does not touch networking</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Does not use sudo internally</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Installs only named scripts you control</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Is fully reversible</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Does not hide behavior behind macros</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Anyone reading it can see:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words"><p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">ŌĆ£These are local analytical scripts with documentation, not exploit tooling.ŌĆØ</p></p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">That matters for:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">reviewers</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">colleagues</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">institutional IT</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">your future self</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Optional (recommended) add-on target</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">If you want to visibly emphasize non-operational status, add this:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">audit:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "=== Spherepop Tool Audit ==="
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "No network access"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "No privileged operations"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "No external targets"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@echo "All tools are local simulations"</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This gives you a one-command rhetorical proof.</p>
