p;_h4:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0"><p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.TH SP-TOOLS 7 "September 2025" "Spherepop Project" "Miscellaneous Information Manuals"
.SH NAME
sp-tools - analytical utilities for studying abstraction, metrics, and epistemic drift</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sp-tools
provides a suite of local command-line utilities for exploring
metric contamination, abstraction collapse, observer effects,
and governance failure modes in complex systems.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B sp-tools
suite consists of small, local, read-only analytical programs.
They are designed to support experimentation, teaching, and
conceptual testing of ideas related to:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.IP (bu 4
Goodhart's Law and proxy optimization
.IP (bu 4
Semantic drift and abstraction collapse
.IP (bu 4
Loss of contextual constraints under simplification
.IP (bu 4
Observer effects and attribution error
.IP (bu 4
Refusal, interruptibility, and governance primitives
.IP (bu 4
Apprenticeship, judgment formation, and institutional fragility</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The tools do not probe networks, scan systems, exploit software,
or interact with external targets. All behavior is confined to
local simulation, logging, and visualization of conceptual dynamics.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH EPISTEMIC STATUS
The utilities in this suite are not diagnostic instruments.
They do not measure real systems, infer ground truth, or detect
actual failures.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Instead, they are epistemic probes: deliberately simplified
models and simulations intended to surface how humans interpret
signals, metrics, and structured output.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Outputs may resemble warnings, monitors, or analyses, but these
representations are illustrative rather than evidentiary.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Users should not treat output as factual claims about real systems.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH TOOL CATEGORIES
The suite is organized around functional roles rather than
operational capability.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SS Metric and Proxy Analysis
Tools in this category explore how metrics diverge from underlying
phenomena when optimized.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Examples include:
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-probe-goodhart
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-drift-metrics</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SS Invariant and Constraint Inspection
These tools model how constraints are preserved, weakened, or erased
under abstraction.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Examples include:
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-check-invariants
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-probe-refusal</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SS Observer and Attribution Simulation
These tools examine how observers infer meaning, authority, or intent
from structured output.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Examples include:
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-sim-observer
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-audit-legibility</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SS Institutional and Developmental Models
These utilities focus on judgment formation, apprenticeship, and
organizational fragility.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Examples include:
.IP (bu 4
.B sp-sim-apprenticeship</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH NON-GOALS
The
.B sp-tools
suite explicitly does not aim to:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.IP (bu 4
Perform security testing or penetration testing
.IP (bu 4
Discover vulnerabilities in real systems
.IP (bu 4
Bypass safeguards or controls
.IP (bu 4
Generate actionable procedures for misuse
.IP (bu 4
Replace formal analysis or empirical study</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Any resemblance to monitoring or testing tools is aesthetic or
illustrative rather than functional.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH DESIGN PRINCIPLES
The tools adhere to the following principles:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.IP (bu 4
Local-only execution
.IP (bu 4
No network access
.IP (bu 4
No privileged operations
.IP (bu 4
Explicit documentation of limitations
.IP (bu 4
Reversible installation and removal
.IP (bu 4
Preference for legibility over cleverness</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH RELATION TO SPHEREPOP AND RSVP
The tools serve as lightweight companions to the Spherepop OS
and RSVP (Relativistic Scalar-Vector Plenum) theoretical frameworks.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">They do not implement those frameworks directly.
Instead, they provide small-scale environments in which concepts
such as event-sourced semantics, refusal, and invariant structure
can be explored informally before formalization.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH ETHICAL CONSIDERATIONS
The project treats epistemic misinterpretation as a first-class risk.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Accordingly, the tools include:
.IP (bu 4
Explicit epistemic disclaimers
.IP (bu 4
Avoidance of authoritative language where unwarranted
.IP (bu 4
Deliberate resistance to over-simplification
.IP (bu 4
Support for interruption and shutdown</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The goal is to improve epistemic hygiene rather than simulate control.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sp-lab (1),
.BR sp-probe-goodhart (1),
.BR sp-drift-metrics (1),
.BR sp-check-invariants (1),
.BR sp-sim-observer (1),
.BR sp-audit-legibility (1),
.BR sp-probe-refusal (1),
.BR sp-sim-apprenticeship (1)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.SH AUTHORS
Spherepop Project Contributors</p>
